sentence: Crude continues to slide on Greek jitters .
Investing.com - Crude oil futures fell in U.S. trading on Friday on growing fears the European economy faces hurdles made higher by a possible Greek exit from the eurozone .

On the New York Mercantile Exchange , light , sweet crude futures for delivery in June traded at USD92 .13 a barrel , down 0.47 % , off from a session high of USD92 .94 and up from an earlier session low of USD91 .63 .
European officials are working on a contingency plan should Greece exit the eurozone .
`` A year and a half ago there maybe was a risk of a domino effect , '' says European Union trade commissioner Karel De Gucht , according to newswire reports .

golden-entity-mentions.text: A year and a half ago

sentence: `` But today there are in the European Central Bank , as well as in the Commission , services working on emergency scenarios if Greece should n't make it .
A Greek exit does not mean the end of the euro , as some claim . ''

Greece is headed for parliamentary elections in June and fears are building that anger over austerity measures slapped on the country in exchange for bailout money will result in strong showing among politicians opposed to harsh rescue-funding terms .
A Greek exit from the eurozone could rattle the broader European economy and crimp oil demand .
Rising U.S. crude stockpiles also continued to push oil down .

The U.S. Energy Information Administration said in its weekly report that U.S. crude oil inventories rose by 2.13 million barrels in the week ended May 11 , above expectations for a 1.74 million barrel increase .
U.S. crude supplies rose by 3.65 million barrels in the preceding week .

The data came in the heels of similar figures released a day earlier by the American Petroleum Institute , an industry group , which reported that U.S. inventories rose 6.6 million barrels last week .
On the ICE Futures Exchange , Brent oil futures for July delivery were up 0.30 % and trading at USD107 .81 a barrel , up USD15 .68 from its U.S. counterpart .
